dataIdInfo.idAbs: California Public Resources Code, Chapter 1.4. California Wild and Scenic Rivers Act, Section 5093.50. It is the policy of the State of California that certain rivers which possess extraordinary scenic, recreational, fishery, or wildlife values shall be preserved in their free-flowing state, together with their immediate environments, for the benefit and enjoyment of the people of the state. The Legislature declares that such use of these rivers is the highest and most beneficial use and is a reasonable and beneficial use of water within the meaning of Section 2 of Article X of the California Constitution. It is the purpose of this chapter to create a California Wild and Scenic Rivers System to be administered in accordance with the provisions of this chapter.Revisions will be conducted on an as-needed basis reflecting additions or amendments to the California Public Resources Code or significant changes to the National Hydrography Dataset NHDFlowline. The associated data are considered DWR enterprise GIS data, which meet all appropriate requirements of the DWR Spatial Data Standards, specifically the DWR Spatial Data Standard version 3.1, dated September 11, 2019. Department of Water Resources (DWR) makes no warranties or guarantees - either expressed or implied - as to the completeness, accuracy, or correctness of the data herein (subject data). The subject data may include data from National Hydrography Dataset. Any data from U.S. Government sources is subject to any conditions, disclaimers, or other restrictions specified by the sources. The official DWR GIS steward for this data set is Jonathan Stephan, who may be contacted at 530-529-7335, or at jonathan.stephan@water.ca.gov. Comments, problems, improvements, updates, or suggestions should be forwarded to the official GIS steward as available and appropriate.
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The State of California Wild, Scenic, and Recreational (WSR) Rivers dataset consists of designated California waterways specified in the California Public Resources Code. Waterway segments are identified by the California Public Resources Code and delineated by the National Hydrography Dataset (NHD). Federally designated WSR streams are not included in this dataset. This version differs from former versions in that it 1) coincides with the NHD flowline feature segments and identifiers, and 2) only includes those California streams that are designated wild, scenic, recreational, or other special case per the California Public Resources Code (PRC) Sections 5093.50 - 5093.71. Federally designated WSR streams are not included in this dataset. This dataset contains point features identifying endpoints of designated Wild and Scenic Rivers with USGS HydroLink attributes.

attrdomv.udom: Sequential unique whole numbers that are automatically generated.

attr.attrdef: Reachcode of the National Hydrography Dataset Plus Version 2.1 (NHDPlusV2.1). If no NHDPlusV2.1 feature exists for association with the record the value is set to 'NO REACHCODE'.

Measure along the reachcode of the National Hydrography Dataset Plus Version 2.1 (NHDPlusV2.1). Values range from 0, referring to the most downstream point of the reach, to 100, referring to the most upstream point of the reach. If no NHDPlusV2.1 feature exists for association with the record the value is set to 'NO MEASURE'.
Reachcode of the USGS National Hydrography Dataset (NHDHR). If no NHDHR feature exists for association with the record the value is set to 'NO REACHCODE'.
Identification key for each administered river.

The verified longitudinal coordinate of the record (point) in decimal degrees (CRS=4269). This coordinate represents the location of the feature, not necessarily where the address is for the NHD representation of the point. If using the HydroLink Tool and a point is relocated (to correct location by user) this value reflects the new location of the point. Note, this field records values with 4 decimal places (scale of 4) although the point geometry retains more precision.
National Hydrography Dataset NHDFlowline unqiue identifier.
Original source of the boundary and attribute information.

Unique identifier for stream segment and catchments of the National Hydrography Dataset Plus Version 2.1. If no NHDPlusV2.1 feature exists for association with the record the value is set to 'NO COMID'.
Geographic Names Information System feature name attributed by the National Hydrography Dataset NHDFlowline.
This is the date when the National Hydrography Dataset High Resolution (NHDHR) reachcode was last modified. Format YYYYMMDD. See 'smdate' in NHD Handbook for additional details.
Geographic Names Information System feature unique identifier attributed by the National Hydrography Dataset NHDFlowline.

Measure along the reachcode of the USGS National Hydrography Dataset (NHDHR). Values range from 0, referring to the most downstream point of the reach, to 100, referring to the most upstream point of the reach. If no NHDHR feature exists for association with the record the value is set to 'NO MEASURE'.

The verified latitudinal coordinate of the record (point) in decimal degrees (CRS=4269). This coordinate represents the location of the feature, not necessarily where the address is for the NHD representation of the point. If using the HydroLink Tool and a point is relocated (to correct location by user) this value reflects the new location of the point. Note, this field records values with 4 decimal places (scale of 4) although the point geometry retains more precision.
